{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d0ae376a-9041-4ffa-850f-618d65c9c077","content":"The .NET MAUI Android build system **ignores `JAVA_HOME`**. It uses its own JDK resolution via the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property, so your Adoptium JDK isn't being picked up.\n\n**Recommended fix — use the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 to a path the build system auto-detects.\n\n**Alternative — point the build at your Adoptium JDK explicitly:**\n\nIn your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr via the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build /p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** `JAVA_HOME` ≠ `JavaSdkDirectory`. The MAUI build has its own JDK lookup. Either install the workload-bundled JDK or set `JavaSdkDirectory` explicitly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"005178b7-fca2-4654-994d-a495a655cf78","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what common issues arise with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java.\n\nThe most common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java is a JDK version compatibility problem. .NET MAUI / Android SDK has specific JDK version requirements:\n\n- .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 MAUI requires JDK 17\n\nBut the key issue is often that the Android Gradle plugin or Android SDK build tools have specific JDK version requirements, and sometimes the JDK that's installed isn't the one being picked up by the build process.\n\n\nThe real problem is that .NET MAUI Android builds rely on the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution that comes with the Android workload, not the system JAVA_HOME variable. When you install the MAUI workload, it places Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 in a specific directory, and MSBuild looks for `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` which might point to a completely different JDK than what the user has set up. Even though the user has Adoptium Temurin JDK 17 installed, the build process might not be using it at all. The .NET Android build system has its own `JavaSdkDirectory` property that it checks, and Adoptium Temurin might not be in the expected locations that the build tools search. The real fix is usually to either use Microsoft's OpenJDK from the MAUI workload or explicitly set `JavaSdkDirectory` in the project configuration. The .NET MAUI build system uses its own JDK resolution through `JavaSdkDirectory` rather than relying on JAVA_HOME, so the most common fix is either installing Microsoft's bundled OpenJDK via the Android workload or explicitly pointing `JavaSdkDirectory` in the project file to an existing JDK installation like Adoptium.","outputTokens":1513,"requestId":"B805:2A1B2F:13606B:19364F:69FFD7AC"},"id":"e5e38966-4aec-4a1f-99b7-f5beb9783f33","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:56:42.424Z","parentId":"89c43ec8-5031-4f00-bced-356e7ac17c23"}
